          <table uk:widths="7.19in">
            <tr>
              <td>
                <p class="ia-table-text"><b>Questions</b></p>
              </td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>
                <p class="ia-table-text"><b>1. What were the policy objectives of the measure? </b>(Maximum 5 lines)</p>
              </td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>
                <p class="ia-table-text">The 2013 Waste Electrical and Electronic Equipment (WEEE) Regulations came into force on the 1st of January 2014. The objectives of the Regulations were: • to ensure compliance with the recast WEEE Directive 2012/19/EU (‘the WEEE Directive’) which aimed to improve the efficiency and effectiveness of the original WEEE Directive by further protecting the environment as well as human and animal health; and • to respond to the concerns expressed by UK electrical and electronic equipment (EEE) producers under the Red Tape Challenge about the cost of meeting their financial obligations under the 2006 WEEE Regulations (the Waste Electrical and Electronic Equipment Regulations 2006 (SI 2006 No. 3289, as amended by SIs 2007 No. 3454, 2009 No. 2957, 2009 No. 3216 and 2010 No. 1155)).</p>
                <p class="ia-table-text" />
              </td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>
                <p class="ia-table-text"><b>2. What evidence has informed the PIR? </b>(Maximum 5 lines)</p>
              </td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>
                <p class="ia-table-text">The Consultation<authorialNote marker="1"><p class="ia-table-text"> Consultation on reforming the producer responsibility system for waste electrical and electronic equipment 2023. Available at: <a href="https://consult.defra.gov.uk/product-regulation-and-producer-responsibility/consultation-on-reforming-the-producer-responsibil/"><u>https://consult.defra.gov.uk/product-regulation-and-producer-responsibility/consultation-on-reforming-the-producer-responsibil/</u></a> </p></authorialNote> on Reforming the Producer Responsibility System for Waste Electrical and Electronic Equipment 2023 and Electrical Waste: Reforming the Producer Responsibility System – Call for Evidence<authorialNote marker="2"><p class="ia-table-text"> Call for evidence on reforming the producer responsibility system for waste electricals 2023. Available at: <a href="https://consult.defra.gov.uk/product-regulation-and-producer-responsibility/call-for-evidence-on-reforming-the-producer-respon/"><u>https://consult.defra.gov.uk/product-regulation-and-producer-responsibility/call-for-evidence-on-reforming-the-producer-respon/</u></a> </p></authorialNote>, the accompanying Impact Assessment<authorialNote marker="3"><p class="ia-table-text">  Reforming the UK producer responsibility system for waste electricals. Available at: <a href="https://consult.defra.gov.uk/product-regulation-and-producer-responsibility/consultation-on-reforming-the-producer-responsibil/supporting_documents/WEEE%20Review%20Impact%20Assessment%20Final%202023.pdf"><u>https://consult.defra.gov.uk/product-regulation-and-producer-responsibility/consultation-on-reforming-the-producer-responsibil/supporting_documents/WEEE%20Review%20Impact%20Assessment%20Final%202023.pdf</u></a> </p></authorialNote> and Summary of Responses to the consultation<authorialNote marker="4"><p class="ia-table-text"> Consultation outcome - Electrical waste: reforming the producer responsibility system. Available at:  <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/consultations/electrical-waste-reforming-the-producer-responsibility-system"><u>https://www.gov.uk/government/consultations/electrical-waste-reforming-the-producer-responsibility-system</u></a> </p></authorialNote> and call for evidence<authorialNote marker="5"><p class="ia-table-text"> Call for evidence outcome - Electrical waste: reforming the producer responsibility system – call for evidence. Available at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/calls-for-evidence/electrical-waste-reforming-the-producer-responsibility-system-call-for-evidence"><u>https://www.gov.uk/government/calls-for-evidence/electrical-waste-reforming-the-producer-responsibility-system-call-for-evidence</u></a> </p></authorialNote> provide the evidence. Those documents with the Government Response constitute the statutory requirements for a PIR under Regulation 93 of the 2013 WEEE Regulations. The consultation and call for evidence take forward policy recommendations from the previous PIR and other measures aimed to drive up levels of separately collected WEEE for re-use/recycling and wider measures designed to embrace the circular economy. </p>
                <p class="ia-table-text" />
              </td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>
                <p class="ia-table-text"><b>3. To what extent have the policy objectives been achieved? </b>(Maximum 5 lines)</p>
              </td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>
                <p class="ia-table-text" />
                <p class="ia-table-text">EU Member State collection targets (45%) were achieved by setting household WEEE collection targets from 2014 onwards and gathering data on household and non household WEEE financed by producers, supplemented by data from other sources. Along with most other member states, the UK was unable to achieve the higher target (65%) between 2019 and leaving the EU. The compliance fee and household WEEE collection targets have been instrumental in decreasing cost of evidence and enabling costs correction of WEEE evidence. There has been high compliance among UK based business but compliance by online businesses - particularly those overseas and more recently amongst producers of vapes - has been lower.</p>
              </td>
            </tr>
          </table>
        </content>
